<H1><CENTER>Edinburgh Parallel Computing Centre</CENTER></H1>
<H1><CENTER>Summer Scholarship Programme</CENTER></H1>
<HR>


<P>

The Summer Scholarship Programme (SSP) is a unique training scheme;
since its inception in 1987, more than 150 senior undergraduates have
been employed to work on 10-week projects looking at various aspects of
High Performance Computing. In 1996 the SSP involved 15 students from 9
different countries; Albania, Canada, France, Germany, Holland, Poland,
Portugal, UK and USA.
<P>
Students are given a one week formal training course and then work on
an assigned project with one, or sometimes two, supervisors. At the
end of the period each project is written up in a formal
report. Electronic versions of the reports are available for <A
href="http://www.epcc.ed.ac.uk/~epccssp/1996/projects96.html">1996</A>,
<A
href="http://www.epcc.ed.ac.uk/~epccssp/1995/projects95.html">1995</A>,
and <A
href="http://www.epcc.ed.ac.uk/~epccssp/1994/projects94.html">1994</A>.
There is also some information on the <A
href="http://www.epcc.ed.ac.uk/~epccssp/students93.html">1993</A> projects.
During their stay the students are
supported by grants from EPCC; competition for
places is fierce with some 200 applicants for the available
spaces.
<P>
Applications have now closed for the 1997 Summer Scholarship Programme.
Details of the application procedure for 1997 have been <A
href="./Applications.html">left on the Web site</A> as next years
applications will be similar.
<P>
Details of how to submit a project for a student to work on can be found
<A href="./ProjProp.html">here.</A>
<P>
At SuperComputing 1994 a past co-ordinator of the programme presented a
paper describing in detail the operation of the programme. A copy of the
paper is available <A
href="http://www.epcc.ed.ac.uk/~epccssp/SC_paper.ps.Z">here</A>
<P>
Finally, any queries related to the SSP should be sent to <A
